description:
The process of biometric user authentication can be outlined as follows (Veeramachaneni et al., 2005):&nbsp; (a) acquisition of raw data;&nbsp; (b) extraction of features from these raw data;&nbsp; (c) computing a score for the similarity or dissimilarity between these features and a previously given set of reference features; and (d) classification with respect to the score, using a threshold. The outcomes of the decision processing steps are either true or false (or accept/reject) for verification purposes, or the user&rsquo;s identity for identification scenarios. 
 The fusion of different signals can be performed (1) at the raw data or the feature level, (2) at the score level, or (3) at the decision level. Each of these approaches has its own advantages and disadvantages. For raw data or feature-level fusion, the base data must be compatible for all modalities and a common matching algorithm (processing step c) must be used. If these conditions are met, the separate feature vectors of the modalities easily could be concatenated into a single new vector. This level of fusion has the advantage that only one algorithm for further processing steps is necessary instead of one for each modality. Another advantage of fusing at this early stage of processing is that no information is lost due to prior processing steps. The main disadvantage is the demand for compatibility among the different raw data or features. The fusion at score level is performed by computing a similarity or dissimilarity (distance) score for each single modality. For joining these different scores, normalization should be done. The straightforward and most rigid approach for fusion is at the decision level. Here, each biometric modality results in its own decision; in the case of a verification scenario this is a set of true's and falsies. From this set a kind of voting (majority decision) or a logical AND or OR decision can be computed. This level of fusion is the least powerful due to the absence of detailed information. However, the advantage of this fusion strategy is the ease and the guaranteed availability of all single-modality decision results. In practice, score-level fusion is the best-researched approach, which appears to result in better improvements of recognition accuracy compared to the other strategies.&nbsp; 
 &nbsp;

